WEBVTT

00:16.154 --> 00:19.053
Narrator: Previously
on "Mountain Men,"

00:19.088 --> 00:21.055
Eustace confronts
the aftermath...

00:21.090 --> 00:22.298
Eustace:
It's all you, Preston.

00:22.332 --> 00:23.920
...of nature's fury.

00:23.954 --> 00:26.612
Eustace:
We had a terrible tornado
come in here.

00:26.647 --> 00:29.374
The destruction
is just overwhelming.

00:29.408 --> 00:31.238
Narrator:
While Marty doubles down...

00:32.894 --> 00:34.689
...from 300 feet up.

00:34.724 --> 00:36.795
Marty: The biggest advantage
to airplane trapping is

00:36.829 --> 00:38.314
just being able
to cover ground,

00:38.348 --> 00:40.419
but it's a risky situation.

00:45.700 --> 00:48.393
Narrator: And Morgan braves
an Alaskan gauntlet...

00:48.427 --> 00:51.120
Morgan: It's without a doubt the
most dangerous thing that I do.

00:51.154 --> 00:53.294
Narrator: ...before winter
locks him in.

00:53.329 --> 00:54.813
Morgan:
The current's too strong.

00:54.847 --> 00:55.917
Whoa!

00:57.471 --> 01:05.824
♪♪

01:09.724 --> 01:12.175
♪♪

01:12.210 --> 01:15.213
Captioning Provided by
A+E Networks

01:17.836 --> 01:20.839
♪♪

01:22.392 --> 01:25.154
Narrator:
When winter settles in,

01:25.188 --> 01:26.845
the freedom of life
in the mountains

01:26.879 --> 01:30.124
becomes a daily fight
to endure

01:30.159 --> 01:32.126
on the edge of survival.

01:35.164 --> 01:38.132
♪♪

01:38.167 --> 01:40.997
On the banks
of Alaska's big river,

01:41.031 --> 01:45.001
Morgan Beasley is racing
the oncoming deep freeze,

01:45.035 --> 01:47.210
trying to complete
a critical supply run

01:47.245 --> 01:49.557
before the river turns to ice.

01:49.592 --> 01:51.801
Morgan: So far, so good
on the float.

01:51.835 --> 01:55.598
There's some ice in the creeks,
but it's not shutting me down.

01:55.632 --> 01:58.601
Narrator:
He set out five days ago
on a 75-mile trek

01:58.635 --> 02:00.292
to the nearest town,

02:00.327 --> 02:02.950
on a mission to stock up
on horse feed,

02:02.984 --> 02:06.195
and other necessities
that he can't get from the land.

02:06.229 --> 02:08.300
Morgan: Been pretty lucky,
the weather has held,

02:08.335 --> 02:11.959
but the weather
can change any day.

02:11.993 --> 02:14.341
I made some good time
in the last couple days,

02:14.375 --> 02:18.172
and I'm getting set up
to maybe get into town today.

02:18.207 --> 02:21.486
I'm probably only 15
or 20 miles away.

02:21.520 --> 02:25.490
Thing that's got me
most concerned is the raft.

02:25.524 --> 02:28.009
Narrator: Morgan's already
repaired one leak

02:28.044 --> 02:31.185
using his only patch kit.

02:31.220 --> 02:34.706
And now there's another
problem brewing.

02:34.740 --> 02:37.502
That raft must have
some other small leak.

02:37.536 --> 02:40.298
Every hour or so,
it seems to get a little soft

02:40.332 --> 02:42.886
and I got to pull over
and blow it up again.

02:42.921 --> 02:46.925
I really want to get to town
today before it gets worse.

02:46.959 --> 02:49.893
There's no way I can make
as good a time

02:49.928 --> 02:53.034
walking as I can on the rivers
with this raft.

02:56.831 --> 02:59.800
The urethane-coated nylon raft
is lightweight,

02:59.834 --> 03:05.323
but vulnerable to jagged ice,
sharp rocks, and other debris.

03:05.357 --> 03:06.910
Morgan: If your raft went under,

03:06.945 --> 03:09.016
you go into
that 32-degree water,

03:09.050 --> 03:11.743
it's 50-50
whether you could swim to shore.

03:11.777 --> 03:14.332
Even with a life jacket,
you won't have the energy

03:14.366 --> 03:16.092
to get yourself up out of it.

03:16.126 --> 03:19.129
♪♪

03:21.270 --> 03:26.585
Definitely some sticks and stuff
here below these rapids

03:26.620 --> 03:28.898
that washed out.

03:28.932 --> 03:30.831
And up in here I got to be
real careful,

03:30.865 --> 03:35.042
stuff like that
could really mess you up.

03:35.076 --> 03:36.768
Got to keep my eyes downstream.

03:36.802 --> 03:41.221
♪♪

03:41.255 --> 03:42.739
Ew.

03:42.774 --> 03:45.570
That's a nasty pile
of stuff there.

03:48.089 --> 03:52.301
Look at this big ice shelf
that broke off in front of me.

03:52.335 --> 03:56.305
That thing is like a meat
cleaver sailing down the river.

03:56.339 --> 03:58.824
I don't want to be too close
to it in case it hits something

03:58.859 --> 04:02.000
and spins and comes at me.

04:02.034 --> 04:03.277
Speaking of that --

04:03.312 --> 04:06.660
It seems like this raft
is losing air again.

04:06.694 --> 04:09.663
♪♪

04:09.697 --> 04:13.218
Yeah, it's definitely down.

04:13.253 --> 04:14.530
Damn it.

04:14.564 --> 04:16.221
The raft is getting soft again.

04:16.256 --> 04:17.981
It's leaking worse.

04:18.016 --> 04:19.845
I have to get
out of the water.

04:22.469 --> 04:25.472
♪♪

04:31.167 --> 04:33.342
[ Exhales sharply ]

04:33.376 --> 04:36.345
♪♪

04:36.379 --> 04:38.312
But this slow leak,
I can't find it.

04:38.347 --> 04:39.865
It's just too small.

04:39.900 --> 04:41.557
I'll just have to make it work.

04:45.354 --> 04:46.803
Better than it was.

04:46.838 --> 04:48.391
I was really counting
on being able

04:48.426 --> 04:50.911
to just float out
to the town today.

04:50.945 --> 04:52.706
Hopefully this raft
will make it,

04:52.740 --> 04:55.053
and it's not gonna
get any worse.

04:55.087 --> 04:58.090
♪♪

05:08.031 --> 05:11.897
Narrator:
Alaska is one of the coldest
places on the continent,

05:11.932 --> 05:13.278
and this winter,

05:13.313 --> 05:17.765
a deep freeze already has
the White Mountains in its grip.

05:17.800 --> 05:20.320
Yesterday, Marty burned
too much daylight

05:20.354 --> 05:22.391
getting his lynx trapline up
and running,

05:22.425 --> 05:25.083
and was forced to bed down
in his plane.

05:25.117 --> 05:28.707
♪♪

05:28.742 --> 05:30.951
Ah.

05:30.985 --> 05:32.573
[ Exhales ]

05:32.608 --> 05:35.507
Cold night.

05:35.542 --> 05:37.267
Narrator: Overnight,
the temperature

05:37.302 --> 05:40.547
plunged to 50 below zero.

05:40.581 --> 05:42.687
Marty: Part of trapping
with an airplane,

05:42.721 --> 05:45.655
sometimes
you get stuck out at night.

05:45.690 --> 05:49.038
That's all part of the game.

05:49.072 --> 05:51.385
It wasn't a whole lot of fun.

05:51.420 --> 05:55.078
Sleeping out in the cold
never is fun.

05:55.113 --> 05:58.496
But, you know, as long
as you can get some rest

05:58.530 --> 06:01.671
and you ain't too cold.

06:01.706 --> 06:04.881
I need to get moving.

06:04.916 --> 06:07.677
Narrator:
Squeezed by the declining
price of marten fur,

06:07.712 --> 06:11.854
Marty is shifting his focus
this season to lynx,

06:11.888 --> 06:14.719
a strategy that depends
on aerial trapping

06:14.753 --> 06:18.826
to cover more ground on the hunt
for the elusive prey.

06:18.861 --> 06:23.762
But extreme subzero conditions
make flying more dangerous.

06:23.797 --> 06:25.281
I put my heater in last night.

06:25.315 --> 06:27.317
I'm just going to see
if it's warm enough

06:27.352 --> 06:29.768
and it didn't go out.

06:29.803 --> 06:32.771
♪♪

06:32.806 --> 06:35.118
Oh, she's just
barely warm enough.

06:35.153 --> 06:37.776
Yeah, I better get her started
pretty quick.

06:37.811 --> 06:41.884
Narrator:
A small propane heater is
Marty's most important lifeline,

06:41.918 --> 06:45.784
thawing oil and fluids
in the engine so it will start.

06:45.819 --> 06:47.993
When I unwrap,
I want to --

06:48.028 --> 06:49.926
I want to fire up
as quick as I can

06:49.961 --> 06:53.689
'cause the engine
is getting cold

06:53.723 --> 06:55.691
the whole time
this cover is off.

06:57.658 --> 07:00.661
♪♪

07:07.496 --> 07:09.774
Narrator:
Marty plans to push on,
despite his rough night

07:09.808 --> 07:12.259
in the brutal cold.

07:12.293 --> 07:13.778
A single lynx is known
to cover up

07:13.812 --> 07:15.918
to 300 square miles
of territory,

07:15.952 --> 07:19.162
making them difficult to track.

07:19.197 --> 07:22.027
With lynx pelts still fetching
several hundred dollars each,

07:22.062 --> 07:23.995
he's counting
on his aerial strategy

07:24.029 --> 07:25.755
to keep him in the black.

07:28.033 --> 07:29.483
I'm gonna take the plane

07:29.518 --> 07:32.762
and hopefully find
a pocket of cats somewhere

07:32.797 --> 07:36.283
I can get to and trap.

07:36.317 --> 07:38.354
That's the big picture plan.

07:41.530 --> 07:44.498
♪♪

07:55.578 --> 07:58.374
Flying in the cold, you want
to keep your oil temp up.

07:58.408 --> 08:01.826
If I'm flying and the oil temp
drops, the engine quits.

08:01.860 --> 08:05.899
♪♪

08:05.933 --> 08:09.385
I could crash the plane,
it would be a bad deal.

08:17.324 --> 08:20.327
♪♪

08:29.716 --> 08:32.408
Narrator:
In Montana's cattle country,

08:32.442 --> 08:34.755
the region's
50,000 head of cattle

08:34.790 --> 08:37.378
are the backbone
of the economy,

08:37.413 --> 08:40.761
but a growing number of wolf
and lion attacks

08:40.796 --> 08:43.143
have the Ruby Valley on edge.

08:43.177 --> 08:45.594
Where Rich Lewis and his hounds
are often the only thing

08:45.628 --> 08:47.837
standing between predator
and prey,

08:47.872 --> 08:52.497
this winter, his pack is thinner
than it's ever been...

08:52.532 --> 08:55.845
just as the danger
is most severe.

08:55.880 --> 08:57.398
I keep losing my old dogs,

08:57.433 --> 09:00.125
and so I've got
to keep young ones coming on.

09:00.160 --> 09:01.610
I breed and raise
my own hounds,

09:01.644 --> 09:03.612
and I need to get
my pack built up

09:03.646 --> 09:05.924
so I'm ready for predators.

09:05.959 --> 09:08.237
Narrator:
The youngest of the pack,
Skillet,

09:08.271 --> 09:10.239
is still too green to hunt lions

09:10.273 --> 09:12.172
without more intensive training.

09:12.206 --> 09:14.139
Skillet's about seven,
eight months old now,

09:14.174 --> 09:17.418
and I want to get her started
on the tracking ability,

09:17.453 --> 09:18.730
getting her to use her nose.

09:18.765 --> 09:20.042
She's got potential.

09:20.076 --> 09:22.389
I mean, she's got
a lot of good blood in her,

09:22.423 --> 09:24.771
so the genetics are there.

09:24.805 --> 09:26.358
Narrator: Rich is hoping that
Skillet will live up

09:26.393 --> 09:28.291
to the legacy
of her mother, Ruby,

09:28.326 --> 09:30.259
who was one of his best hunters,

09:30.293 --> 09:33.918
until she died last winter
while birthing Skillet's litter.

09:33.952 --> 09:35.367
Ruby was a good dog.

09:35.402 --> 09:37.335
She was one of
my football players, I call her,

09:37.369 --> 09:38.819
because I could
always put her in.

09:38.854 --> 09:40.649
Hopefully
Skillet fills in my pack.

09:40.683 --> 09:42.236
I'm hoping she's gonna
be a superstar,

09:42.271 --> 09:44.376
but I got to work her
with some older dogs

09:44.411 --> 09:47.587
so she kind of learns
and gets the knack of things.

09:47.621 --> 09:48.898
Skillet.

09:48.933 --> 09:50.624
Skillet, good girl.

09:50.659 --> 09:52.108
Good girl.

09:52.143 --> 09:55.525
Good girl.

09:55.560 --> 09:58.183
Narrator: Today's training
exercise is designed to evaluate

09:58.218 --> 10:00.945
the dynamics
of this three-dog team --

10:00.979 --> 10:04.362
A mix of different ages
and skill sets.

10:04.396 --> 10:07.158
Rich:
Zipper has some experience,
but I keep wanting to train her.

10:07.192 --> 10:08.608
She's gonna be
a really good dog.

10:08.642 --> 10:10.161
I have a lot of faith in her.

10:10.195 --> 10:12.128
And I have Capone,
he's the old pro.

10:12.163 --> 10:14.406
So if Skillet doesn't
take to track,

10:14.441 --> 10:15.580
the other dogs will take it

10:15.615 --> 10:17.340
and she'll go with them
and kind of learn.

10:17.375 --> 10:19.411
It's a learning process for her.

10:19.446 --> 10:22.691
Narrator: The goal is to locate
and track a scent together

10:22.725 --> 10:24.727
and without let up.

10:24.762 --> 10:25.935
Rich: What I'm going to do

10:25.970 --> 10:28.731
is I'm going to lay
a drag with scent on it.

10:28.766 --> 10:32.632
This is a piece of rabbit hide
I'm gonna use for my drag.

10:32.666 --> 10:35.496
I'm going to pour
a little water on it.

10:35.531 --> 10:41.641
So it's softens up a little,
makes my scent last longer.

10:41.675 --> 10:43.919
This is pure bobcat piss.

10:43.953 --> 10:48.475
I'm simulating the same scent
that they smell in the tracks.

10:48.509 --> 10:51.305
A cat, they bury their urine
or their scat,

10:51.340 --> 10:55.689
so that's where a lot of their
scent comes from, on their feet.

10:55.724 --> 10:57.967
So what I'm going to do
is I'm going to take this

10:58.002 --> 11:00.832
and drag it over
through the snow here,

11:00.867 --> 11:02.592
back and forth and around.

11:04.802 --> 11:08.115
I'm gonna raise
the cage up in the tree.

11:08.150 --> 11:10.704
I want to get it up high enough,
but out in the open

11:10.739 --> 11:12.706
so she'll be able to see it.

11:12.741 --> 11:16.745
♪♪

11:16.779 --> 11:20.300
Narrator:
Suspending the hide in a roll
cage helps train the dogs

11:20.334 --> 11:24.545
to track the action
of a cat as its treed.

11:24.580 --> 11:26.755
Rich: My whole goal here
is I want to teach Skillet

11:26.789 --> 11:28.791
to locate the animal
in the tree,

11:28.826 --> 11:30.897
looking up is
what they have to do.

11:30.931 --> 11:33.002
And they have to look up
and see it and smell it,

11:33.037 --> 11:35.246
then they should
start treeing on it.

11:35.280 --> 11:37.110
Come on, Zipper.

11:38.525 --> 11:40.596
[ Zipper whines ]

11:40.630 --> 11:42.149
Come on.

11:42.184 --> 11:43.875
Good girl.

11:43.910 --> 11:45.049
You ready to run?

11:45.083 --> 11:46.740
[ Zipper barks ]Good girl.

11:46.775 --> 11:47.845
Get 'em.

11:47.879 --> 11:49.363
[ Bells jingle ]

11:49.398 --> 11:51.227
I'm gonna let you go.

11:57.544 --> 11:59.339
She's on it there.

12:00.996 --> 12:04.275
What's going on?

12:04.309 --> 12:06.449
They didn't take my drag?

12:06.484 --> 12:09.142
They went up the canyon.

12:09.176 --> 12:10.522
Picked up something else.

12:10.557 --> 12:13.008
[ Dog barks ]

12:13.042 --> 12:15.493
There's Capone right there
in the open.

12:15.527 --> 12:16.805
I got to see what
the heck's going on there.

12:16.839 --> 12:19.359
There's got to be
a track somewhere.

12:19.393 --> 12:20.774
I'm hoping it's not
a mountain lion

12:20.809 --> 12:23.052
because it could get real ugly.

12:23.087 --> 12:26.055
♪♪

12:30.473 --> 12:32.959
♪♪

12:32.993 --> 12:36.376
Narrator: 400 feet above
Alaska's Hard Luck Creek,

12:36.410 --> 12:40.000
the air temperature
is a chilling 50-below zero,

12:40.035 --> 12:43.659
cold enough to congeal the oil
that keeps the plane running.

12:49.699 --> 12:51.080
If Marty can't stabilize

12:51.115 --> 12:54.014
the oil temperature
at 160 degrees,

12:54.049 --> 12:56.741
his engine will fail.

12:56.776 --> 12:59.951
Marty: My hope is to get up,
find warmer air up above.

13:11.791 --> 13:12.999
Narrator: Marty's counting
on the phenomenon

13:13.033 --> 13:16.416
of temperature inversion
to keep him aloft.

13:16.450 --> 13:19.833
Cold air is heavy
and sinks toward the ground,

13:19.868 --> 13:21.248
below bands of warmer air

13:21.283 --> 13:23.837
that sit at higher altitudes.

13:23.872 --> 13:26.564
Marty: If I don't find
warmer air above,

13:26.598 --> 13:29.256
the plane can quit unexpectedly

13:29.291 --> 13:31.914
and I could crash.

13:31.949 --> 13:35.124
Narrator:
It'll be more difficult
to spot lynx from this height,

13:35.159 --> 13:38.921
but Marty has no choice
if he wants to fly safe.

14:06.915 --> 14:08.917
Marty scans for any pattern
of breakage

14:08.951 --> 14:10.780
in the fresh snowpack below.

14:39.982 --> 14:42.191
Descending into the frozen
zone in order

14:42.226 --> 14:44.780
to find a suitable
landing strip,

14:44.814 --> 14:46.540
Marty exposes his engine

14:46.575 --> 14:48.991
to the brutal cold once again.

15:11.013 --> 15:14.016
♪♪

15:29.204 --> 15:32.034
[ Sighs ]

15:32.069 --> 15:34.934
I want to get the engine cover
on as quick as I can

15:34.968 --> 15:38.075
'cause it's pretty
cold out down here.

15:38.109 --> 15:39.731
[ Sighs ]

15:42.734 --> 15:44.667
[ Grunts ]

15:44.702 --> 15:47.015
The main thing is
keep the engine warm.

15:50.846 --> 15:53.849
Heat is a precious commodity
in this country.

15:53.883 --> 15:56.024
Once the engine
is off and covered,

15:56.058 --> 15:59.855
I've only got a couple hours.

15:59.889 --> 16:01.305
And when you are
airplane trapping,

16:01.339 --> 16:02.996
time is of the essence.

16:03.031 --> 16:07.621
So you want to set and go
as quick as you can.

16:11.487 --> 16:14.007
You see the track?
You're set.

16:14.042 --> 16:15.767
I like to use cubbies
a lot of times

16:15.802 --> 16:18.011
'cause cubby's good
for everything --

16:18.046 --> 16:20.910
Lynx, wolverine, fox.

16:20.945 --> 16:23.948
The cubby set is
just, uh, putting branches

16:23.983 --> 16:25.294
and stuff around the traps

16:25.329 --> 16:27.538
so that if a lynx
wants to check out the bait,

16:27.572 --> 16:29.885
he has to go over the trap
to get to it.

16:29.919 --> 16:32.267
Okay, done.

16:32.301 --> 16:35.787
I'll head back to the plane
and hopefully have some critters

16:35.822 --> 16:37.582
when I come back again.

16:37.617 --> 16:40.827
♪♪

16:40.861 --> 16:42.001
Hit and move, hit and move.

16:42.035 --> 16:43.726
That's what it's all about.

16:43.761 --> 16:45.935
Now I'll fly to the next spot.

16:49.974 --> 16:52.977
♪♪

17:01.744 --> 17:03.988
Narrator: In the Ruby Valley,

17:04.023 --> 17:08.648
a routine training exercise
has suddenly become a live hunt.

17:08.682 --> 17:12.272
[ Dogs barking ]

17:12.307 --> 17:13.963
Kind of going that way.

17:13.998 --> 17:18.485
Narrator:
And Rich's youngest dog Skillet
is caught up in the chase.

17:18.520 --> 17:20.004
Rich: I'm starting to get
a little nervous.

17:20.039 --> 17:21.419
I'm hoping it's not
a mountain lion

17:21.454 --> 17:24.940
because Skillet is not real
experienced on doing this.

17:24.974 --> 17:26.769
A dog that doesn't have
a lot of experience,

17:26.804 --> 17:28.288
what happens is
they're wound up,

17:28.323 --> 17:30.532
everything's going on while
they're running around,

17:30.566 --> 17:31.981
not paying attention.

17:32.016 --> 17:33.811
So they get killed right away.

17:33.845 --> 17:36.883
The lion grabs them and bites
them in the head and it's over.

17:36.917 --> 17:39.541
Narrator: The dogs are trained
to lock onto a scent

17:39.575 --> 17:41.543
and track it relentlessly.

17:41.577 --> 17:43.303
Once they're off and running,

17:43.338 --> 17:47.204
they won't stop
until the predator is cornered.

17:47.238 --> 17:49.930
A bobcat, they're on a bobcat.

17:49.965 --> 17:52.071
There's the tracks.
They're pretty fresh.

17:52.105 --> 17:54.487
Went right through here.

17:54.521 --> 17:56.489
Got to be up here somewhere.

17:56.523 --> 17:58.767
This will be really good
training for Skillet, though.

17:58.801 --> 18:00.113
I'm pretty excited.

18:00.148 --> 18:02.702
This is a lot better than that
roll cage and the drag.

18:02.736 --> 18:04.393
This is the real deal here.

18:04.428 --> 18:06.706
[ Dogs barking ]

18:06.740 --> 18:09.260
There's Capone.

18:09.295 --> 18:10.986
God, they've got to be
right up here.

18:14.196 --> 18:17.165
♪♪

18:17.199 --> 18:19.443
There they are.

18:19.477 --> 18:22.273
They got that bobcat
bayed up on the ground.

18:22.308 --> 18:24.103
Good girl.

18:24.137 --> 18:25.725
[ Dogs barking, growling ]Good girl.

18:27.416 --> 18:28.728
Oh, watch out.

18:28.762 --> 18:30.833
Ooh.

18:30.868 --> 18:32.835
Go ahead, Skillet.

18:32.870 --> 18:34.527
Don't back off.

18:37.185 --> 18:38.082
Hey!

18:45.572 --> 18:47.229
There goes the bobcat.

18:47.264 --> 18:48.472
Get on him, get on him.

18:48.506 --> 18:49.887
Let's go.

18:49.921 --> 18:52.821
They're on it.

18:52.855 --> 18:55.927
Yeah, the bobcat bayed up
on the ground here

18:55.962 --> 18:58.758
and, uh, must have got
tired out in the open,

18:58.792 --> 19:00.656
no place to go in a tree,

19:00.691 --> 19:02.348
so they kind of fought
on the ground a little bit,

19:02.382 --> 19:03.970
and then it took off
running again.

19:04.004 --> 19:06.455
Hopefully they get that
bobcat up a tree.

19:06.490 --> 19:09.769
Narrator:
Bobcats are acrobatic jumpers
and can run at speeds

19:09.803 --> 19:11.874
of up to 30 miles an hour.

19:11.909 --> 19:14.256
Rich: A bobcat is a lot harder
to tree than a lion,

19:14.291 --> 19:16.948
because they like to run
and jump and lose the dogs.

19:16.983 --> 19:18.502
It's kind of a game
for them, also,

19:18.536 --> 19:21.746
'cause they'll jump
20 feet off a rock.

19:21.781 --> 19:24.370
You know, it takes the dogs 15
to 20 minutes to figure out

19:24.404 --> 19:26.544
where the bobcat is
'cause they lost the scent.

19:27.752 --> 19:29.823
[ Dogs howling ]

19:31.239 --> 19:32.826
They're going up this way,
I can hear them,

19:32.861 --> 19:34.552
but I can't tell
what they're doing.

19:36.416 --> 19:38.832
♪♪

19:38.867 --> 19:41.490
It looks like the dogs
pushed him quite a ways.

19:43.837 --> 19:46.806
♪♪

19:46.840 --> 19:50.050
There's the bobcat in the tree.

19:50.085 --> 19:51.362
Good girl, Skillet.

19:51.397 --> 19:52.846
Good job, Capone.

19:52.881 --> 19:55.573
Attaboy.

19:55.608 --> 19:58.507
Come on, Skillet.

19:58.542 --> 20:02.304
Capone and Zipper,
they got the bobcat in the tree.

20:02.339 --> 20:04.237
Skillet's not quite sure
of herself.

20:04.272 --> 20:06.998
She's not treeing, but she's
running around, smelling.

20:10.864 --> 20:12.245
Good girl.

20:12.280 --> 20:14.178
Good girl.

20:14.213 --> 20:15.800
She's at the tree,
but she's still,

20:15.835 --> 20:17.802
she's not paying attention.
You know.

20:17.837 --> 20:19.390
Just needs a lot of work.

20:19.425 --> 20:22.945
She's still got
a lot of puppy in her.

20:22.980 --> 20:24.361
Good girl.

20:24.395 --> 20:27.709
How's your ear?
That bobcat got you, huh?

20:27.743 --> 20:29.228
But not too bad.

20:29.262 --> 20:30.953
Good girl.

20:30.988 --> 20:32.196
Come on, let's go.

20:32.231 --> 20:34.336
Capone, here.

20:34.371 --> 20:35.337
All right, cat.

20:35.372 --> 20:36.994
It's your lucky day.

20:37.028 --> 20:38.513
It's a good start for Skillet.

20:38.547 --> 20:40.342
I know she's got it
in her blood,

20:40.377 --> 20:43.138
so I'll just keep working
until it comes out of her.

20:43.172 --> 20:45.899
Now she knows what a bobcat is,

20:45.934 --> 20:47.901
so it'll just
keep getting better.

20:50.801 --> 20:53.804
♪♪

21:00.017 --> 21:03.710
Narrator:
The ancient Ozark range cuts
through the American heartland,

21:03.745 --> 21:05.091
riven with hollows

21:05.125 --> 21:07.680
that shelter herds of wild game

21:07.714 --> 21:10.545
and fields of fertile soil.

21:10.579 --> 21:13.133
Jason Hawk is a native son
of the mountains,

21:13.168 --> 21:16.654
who returned last winter
after a 28-year absence

21:16.689 --> 21:19.036
to build a new life
for his family

21:19.070 --> 21:21.970
in the place
his ancestors called home.

21:23.212 --> 21:27.078
Jason:
My wife and I, we both grew up
with this kind of lifestyle.

21:27.113 --> 21:29.426
We just want to pass it
around to our daughter.

21:29.460 --> 21:32.083
Narrator: Last year,
Jason spent his savings to buy

21:32.118 --> 21:34.465
and restore
this 600-acre property.

21:34.500 --> 21:39.021
But now a family tragedy has
thrown him back to square one.

21:39.056 --> 21:41.230
Jason: It's been a hell of
a spring and a summer.

21:41.265 --> 21:44.924
My dad wound up
getting sick at 75.

21:44.958 --> 21:47.616
He had had several
bypasses on his heart.

21:47.651 --> 21:50.309
Had to go back to Arizona
to take care of him,

21:50.343 --> 21:52.587
and he wound up passing away.

21:52.621 --> 21:55.279
He was able to go at home
with people around him

21:55.314 --> 21:56.487
that loved him.

21:56.522 --> 21:57.937
That felt good to me.

21:57.971 --> 22:01.043
But in the process,
it took a lot of money

22:01.078 --> 22:02.528
and a lot of time.

22:02.562 --> 22:05.841
Narrator: Facing a mountain
of medical and funeral expenses,

22:05.876 --> 22:08.913
Jason sold his homestead
to pay off the debts.

22:11.053 --> 22:14.643
The family has been camping on
a friend's property ever since.

22:14.678 --> 22:17.819
But with winter's arrival,
Jason and Mary need

22:17.853 --> 22:20.753
to find a permanent home fast.

22:23.203 --> 22:26.310
-It's chilly out here.
-Did you sleep warm?

22:26.345 --> 22:28.485
It's a pretty big yawn
for such a little girl.

22:28.519 --> 22:31.142
Mary: Jason's dad passing away
from a heart attack

22:31.177 --> 22:33.973
really knocked us down
for quite a while,

22:34.007 --> 22:36.182
and we finally got back up

22:36.216 --> 22:39.047
and decided
to come back to Arkansas.

22:39.081 --> 22:42.430
And we're looking
for a new start.

22:42.464 --> 22:43.879
Jason: I grew up in Arkansas.

22:43.914 --> 22:45.156
We've got roots here,

22:45.191 --> 22:47.952
so we're trying to reestablish
a foothold here.

22:47.987 --> 22:51.231
And mission right now
is find a section of property.

22:51.266 --> 22:54.580
I've contacted every friend
and everybody I know back here

22:54.614 --> 22:56.236
about finding a place.

22:56.271 --> 22:57.824
Mary:
So what's the plan today?

22:57.859 --> 23:01.863
We have any properties
that you want to go look at?

23:01.897 --> 23:04.072
I'm sure there will be
some leads coming in soon.

23:04.106 --> 23:06.661
While we're looking,
let's focus on adding

23:06.695 --> 23:09.733
whatever we can
to the piggy bank.

23:09.767 --> 23:10.734
Are you gonna be
good at school?

23:10.768 --> 23:11.873
Yeah.
Yeah.

23:11.907 --> 23:13.357
Study hard.
Come on.

23:13.392 --> 23:14.358
All right, come on baby.

23:14.393 --> 23:15.601
Let's go.

23:15.635 --> 23:17.396
All right,
we'll see you in a bit.

23:17.430 --> 23:19.984
Jason: Working on a dream
and having it all go to [bleep]

23:20.019 --> 23:21.710
when you've got a wife
and a kid,

23:21.745 --> 23:23.919
that's a horrible feeling.

23:23.954 --> 23:26.819
River: Bye Dad.
I love you.

23:26.853 --> 23:28.993
See you when I get back.

23:29.028 --> 23:31.789
All right, baby.

23:31.824 --> 23:33.446
Right now,
priorities are simple --

23:33.481 --> 23:34.723
Make sure the family
is comfortable,

23:34.758 --> 23:37.174
keep your head down,
get the work done,

23:37.208 --> 23:39.210
and find a piece of land.

23:39.245 --> 23:41.696
Narrator: Jason's counting
on his skills as a bladesmith

23:41.730 --> 23:43.525
to build the family's war chest

23:43.560 --> 23:46.217
while they search
for a new home.

23:46.252 --> 23:49.255
Jason: Lot of different ways to
forge, and to forge like this,

23:49.289 --> 23:50.705
it's not the ideal situation,

23:50.739 --> 23:53.708
but in this circumstance,
it works.

23:53.742 --> 23:57.332
Narrator: He's improvised an
outdoor forge using a firebox,

23:57.366 --> 24:00.093
a chimney,
and a makeshift bellows.

24:00.128 --> 24:03.994
All a forge is, it's a fancy
campfire with an air supply.

24:04.028 --> 24:05.547
If you know that,
you can build a forge

24:05.582 --> 24:07.722
under most circumstances.

24:07.756 --> 24:09.655
You just got to figure
something out.

24:09.689 --> 24:12.243
I just want to get it so
there's not too much air

24:12.278 --> 24:13.797
escaping out of this thing.

24:13.831 --> 24:16.593
Ooh.

24:16.627 --> 24:17.732
Nice.

24:17.766 --> 24:19.492
Once that heats up evenly,

24:19.527 --> 24:21.218
it's time to hammer out a blade.

24:21.252 --> 24:24.186
Every day I'm not out there
hammering, I'm losing money.

24:26.188 --> 24:29.191
♪♪

24:35.094 --> 24:37.855
Narrator: On Alaska's big river,

24:37.890 --> 24:40.789
the slow leak
in Morgan's inflatable raft

24:40.824 --> 24:42.929
is trying his patience.

24:42.964 --> 24:46.519
So far, he's made two stops
to re-inflate,

24:46.554 --> 24:49.626
a tedious process that involves
climbing to shore

24:49.660 --> 24:51.593
across thin shelf ice,

24:51.628 --> 24:53.319
pumping air and launching

24:53.353 --> 24:56.702
into the frozen river
again and again.

24:56.736 --> 24:58.635
Morgan:
I just stopped and blew it up.

24:58.669 --> 25:01.534
It's already getting soft again.

25:01.569 --> 25:05.434
I don't know if the ice
is opening the holes or what,

25:05.469 --> 25:08.645
but it's definitely down.

25:08.679 --> 25:11.440
Narrator: He's traveled 10 miles
in the last three hours,

25:11.475 --> 25:14.443
a pace that's faster
than hiking in the bush,

25:14.478 --> 25:16.791
but is far behind schedule.

25:16.825 --> 25:19.932
♪♪

25:19.966 --> 25:21.968
At this rate,
he'll struggle to make it

25:22.003 --> 25:25.316
to town before nightfall.

25:25.351 --> 25:27.560
Morgan:
There's a lot of ice shelf
on this river.

25:27.595 --> 25:29.079
That makes it hard to land.

25:29.113 --> 25:30.356
[ Grunts ]

25:34.187 --> 25:35.326
Whoa!

25:38.019 --> 25:40.297
[Bleep]

25:40.331 --> 25:42.610
[Bleep], [bleep], [bleep]

25:42.644 --> 25:45.440
Getting out of the raft
and 20 feet of ice shelf

25:45.474 --> 25:46.510
just breaks off

25:46.545 --> 25:47.891
when I get my weight on to it,

25:47.925 --> 25:51.722
and there goes my paddle
over the side.

25:51.757 --> 25:55.070
[Bleep]

25:55.105 --> 25:57.521
Aw, come on.

25:57.556 --> 25:58.798
[ Grunts ]

25:58.833 --> 26:01.387
Okay.

26:01.421 --> 26:03.044
Let's try a different spot.

26:08.118 --> 26:10.534
This one looks doable.

26:13.019 --> 26:15.056
That was close.

26:15.090 --> 26:18.162
There it goes.
Damn chunk.

26:18.197 --> 26:21.821
Having to launch and land
at these random places

26:21.856 --> 26:23.996
is just making things
a little more risky.

26:24.030 --> 26:26.826
The more time that I have to get
out to blow this thing up,

26:26.861 --> 26:29.657
the more of these maneuvers
I've got to make.

26:29.691 --> 26:31.693
But if I had
to bushwhack from here,

26:31.728 --> 26:34.109
it would be another day
of extra travel.

26:36.491 --> 26:38.286
And I'll just get some more air
in this thing

26:38.320 --> 26:41.738
and get it on the river.

26:41.772 --> 26:43.394
I'm going to float
as much as I can.

26:43.429 --> 26:45.673
Hopefully I can get
to town tonight.

26:47.606 --> 26:52.749
♪♪

26:52.783 --> 26:55.337
Narrator: Coming up...

26:55.372 --> 26:57.788
at his temporary
blacksmith's forge,

26:57.823 --> 27:00.342
Jason's getting started on
a new commission

27:00.377 --> 27:02.586
for a rare blade.

27:02.621 --> 27:05.589
Got a local guy who wants me
to do, uh, a bolo,

27:05.624 --> 27:08.765
it's like an Indonesian-style
jungle blade,

27:08.799 --> 27:10.180
large machete.

27:10.214 --> 27:12.423
What I'm thinking about is
a little bit different design,

27:12.458 --> 27:15.495
it would be all one piece,
solid.

27:15.530 --> 27:19.465
But we're gonna give it
a little bit of a -- a belly

27:19.499 --> 27:22.192
and a slight curve.

27:22.226 --> 27:24.539
This particular bolo,
the price tag is gonna be

27:24.573 --> 27:26.610
about 450 bucks for it.

27:26.645 --> 27:29.820
Orders like this,
it's my bread and butter.

27:29.855 --> 27:32.685
Narrator:
Heating the salvaged steel
to 1,500 degrees

27:32.720 --> 27:35.136
makes it malleable enough
to shape.

27:36.965 --> 27:40.003
Jason: So right now
I've got to establish the tip.

27:40.037 --> 27:41.694
[ Clanging ]

27:41.729 --> 27:44.283
♪♪

27:44.317 --> 27:45.733
A little more heat.

27:45.767 --> 27:49.219
We're just really trying to
widen this thing out right now.

27:49.253 --> 27:51.152
So like this,
this little belly,

27:51.186 --> 27:52.463
that little sweet spot,

27:52.498 --> 27:55.363
that's where the best place
for chopping is gonna be.

27:57.537 --> 27:58.815
Got a good bend.

27:58.849 --> 28:03.026
We've got a full on,
a little bit of a recurve,

28:03.060 --> 28:05.718
just defining this heel area
a little bit.

28:05.753 --> 28:07.720
[ Clanging ]

28:07.755 --> 28:10.136
♪♪

28:10.171 --> 28:14.244
Now that we've got the blade
pretty much roughed in,

28:14.278 --> 28:16.315
just gonna start
adding some forge marks,

28:16.349 --> 28:19.456
sort of giving it a really nice
little forge texture pattern.

28:23.046 --> 28:25.393
Narrator: The bolo knife hails
from the Philippines,

28:25.427 --> 28:29.190
where it is used
as both a weapon and a tool.

28:29.224 --> 28:32.676
Its curved blade is efficient at
hacking through thick sugarcane

28:32.711 --> 28:34.989
and dense jungle vegetation.

28:35.023 --> 28:39.683
About as close as you
can get to a bolo.

28:39.718 --> 28:41.823
What I'm getting ready to do
is quench this blade.

28:41.858 --> 28:45.447
Narrator:
Quenching hot steel and oil
changes its molecular structure

28:45.482 --> 28:47.035
and hardens the blade.

28:47.070 --> 28:48.243
But the quenching process

28:48.278 --> 28:50.176
depends on controlling
temperatures,

28:50.211 --> 28:52.972
which can quickly go wrong
in the open air.

28:53.007 --> 28:54.629
Jason: Working out in the cold
sucks.

28:54.663 --> 28:56.320
With temperature changes,

28:56.355 --> 28:58.598
you really have to watch
what you're doing.

28:58.633 --> 29:00.669
And for me,
when something goes south,

29:00.704 --> 29:02.292
it's a paycheck.

29:02.326 --> 29:04.743
I don't get paid if this knife
doesn't turn out.

29:04.777 --> 29:06.227
Almost there.

29:06.261 --> 29:07.435
We've got a few seconds,

29:07.469 --> 29:08.988
I've got to drop this thing
into the quench.

29:09.023 --> 29:10.645
This is where you make it
or break it.

29:10.679 --> 29:13.682
♪♪

29:17.514 --> 29:20.448
When you first quench a blade,
it gets really hard.

29:20.482 --> 29:21.932
Too hard, so it's brittle.

29:21.967 --> 29:23.347
It's like glass.

29:27.558 --> 29:29.802
The blade looks good,
looks straight.

29:29.837 --> 29:31.355
I don't see any cracks.

29:31.390 --> 29:32.425
That's nice.

29:32.460 --> 29:34.220
The quench has gone well.

29:34.255 --> 29:37.258
Narrator: One last blast of heat
tempers the blade

29:37.292 --> 29:39.260
and reduces its brittleness.

29:41.572 --> 29:42.642
Jason:
Just cool it off to make sure

29:42.677 --> 29:44.644
that it's not climbing
any temperature.

29:44.679 --> 29:46.094
The temper is looking good.

29:46.129 --> 29:49.649
It holds a real good edge,
but it can take some abuse.

29:49.684 --> 29:51.272
That's the point of tempering.

29:51.306 --> 29:53.757
Everything's looking great
at this point.

29:56.415 --> 29:59.418
♪♪

30:03.353 --> 30:05.976
Narrator: In the frozen north,
Morgan's making

30:06.011 --> 30:08.254
a final push toward
his destination

30:08.289 --> 30:10.463
as the daylight fades.

30:10.498 --> 30:13.915
Morgan: I swung into a big wide
channel, huge wide open,

30:13.950 --> 30:16.193
biggest piece of water
I've been on so far.

30:16.228 --> 30:17.677
So that's a good sign.

30:17.712 --> 30:19.093
Means I'm close to the village,

30:19.127 --> 30:21.647
it's just right off
this confluence.

30:22.890 --> 30:24.581
[ Airplane roars ]

30:24.615 --> 30:26.859
♪♪

30:26.894 --> 30:29.068
Okay.
Cool.

30:29.103 --> 30:31.864
That plane must have just taken
off right from the village.

30:31.899 --> 30:34.418
Narrator: He's never taken
this route to town before,

30:34.453 --> 30:36.904
and is navigating
by a combination of maps

30:36.938 --> 30:38.284
and instinct.

30:38.319 --> 30:42.599
If he's on track, he should be
just five miles out.

30:42.633 --> 30:44.739
Morgan: I don't want
to push my luck with the raft.

30:44.773 --> 30:47.466
It's just making things
a little more risky.

30:47.500 --> 30:50.434
I just got to find some place
I can get in to shore.

30:50.469 --> 30:52.885
Maybe there's something
right around the corner here.

30:55.060 --> 30:56.924
Oh! Here we go.

30:56.958 --> 30:58.926
Oh, yeah, come on.

30:58.960 --> 31:01.135
Ooh, sand.

31:03.309 --> 31:06.381
♪♪

31:11.800 --> 31:15.114
I'm happy the raft made it
and that patch held.

31:16.840 --> 31:18.807
Shouldn't be too far
to the village.

31:18.842 --> 31:20.879
But I don't know
exactly where I am,

31:20.913 --> 31:23.019
so I am gonna
just head inland here,

31:23.053 --> 31:24.710
off the floodplain

31:24.744 --> 31:27.161
and see if I can hit a trail.

31:30.233 --> 31:33.236
♪♪

31:35.755 --> 31:37.309
Hey, cool.

31:37.343 --> 31:40.519
It looks like a little
four-wheeler trail or something.

31:40.553 --> 31:42.555
Oh! There's footprints.

31:42.590 --> 31:44.833
Dog prints.

31:44.868 --> 31:47.802
That tells me that
I'm not too far from town.

31:47.836 --> 31:49.321
Narrator:
This is the closest Morgan

31:49.355 --> 31:53.325
has been to civilization
in over a year.

31:53.359 --> 31:56.742
Morgan: Hopefully I can get
in before the stores close.

31:56.776 --> 31:59.745
I've got to start worrying
about stuff like that.

31:59.779 --> 32:02.610
Well, looks like a bigger road
right up ahead.

32:05.371 --> 32:07.442
Hopefully it's just
around the bend.

32:09.997 --> 32:12.931
♪♪

32:18.039 --> 32:20.041
Narrator:
In the Great White North,

32:20.076 --> 32:22.941
Marty's bet his season
on aerial trapping

32:22.975 --> 32:24.804
to help make up
for what's expected to be

32:24.839 --> 32:27.152
a low profit winter.

32:27.186 --> 32:30.362
Spotting from 400 feet up
allows him to cover more ground

32:30.396 --> 32:33.192
and find animal sign
across a wider range,

32:33.227 --> 32:34.953
which should increase his yield.

32:34.987 --> 32:37.645
But relying
on a lightweight aircraft

32:37.679 --> 32:40.751
in subzero conditions is risky.

32:47.379 --> 32:50.382
Marty:
Flying in wind
isn't as, uh, big a deal

32:50.416 --> 32:51.900
as flying in turbulence.

32:51.935 --> 32:56.146
The worst thing is turbulence
because that's bouncy and rough.

32:56.181 --> 33:00.323
And an airplane's a pretty
delicate piece of equipment.

33:00.357 --> 33:03.015
Narrator: In the mountains,
when a warm upper air pocket

33:03.050 --> 33:04.706
hits a heavy cold mass,

33:04.741 --> 33:06.812
it agitates enough rough air

33:06.846 --> 33:09.332
to blow a plane
all over the sky.

33:28.178 --> 33:31.043
Marty: At some point,
the turbulence could be so bad

33:31.078 --> 33:35.668
that you're gonna start
causing damage to the plane.

33:35.703 --> 33:39.086
Narrator: Luckily, Marty
is closing in on his cabin.

34:09.392 --> 34:12.395
♪♪

34:17.986 --> 34:19.919
Marty: [ Laughs ]

34:26.374 --> 34:27.548
[ Grunts ]

34:28.928 --> 34:30.585
[ Sighs ]

34:30.620 --> 34:32.967
Well, glad to be back.

34:33.001 --> 34:35.452
Getting a little rough up there.

34:35.487 --> 34:38.317
It's definitely a wild winter.

34:38.352 --> 34:40.940
Plane trapping is a challenge.

34:40.975 --> 34:43.771
But tomorrow is another day,
we'll see what tomorrow brings.

34:43.805 --> 34:46.808
♪♪

34:54.368 --> 34:57.233
Narrator: Back in the lower 48,

34:57.267 --> 35:00.305
Jason's bolo knife
is taking shape,

35:00.339 --> 35:03.446
but earning this commission
is a family effort.

35:03.480 --> 35:07.553
We have knife orders that
there is no way that we can fill

35:07.588 --> 35:10.556
unless we can make
the whole thing together.

35:10.591 --> 35:15.389
Making a leather sheath rather
than a wooden or another one

35:15.423 --> 35:17.322
gives it a really
good finished look.

35:17.356 --> 35:19.117
Narrator: Jason forges blades,

35:19.151 --> 35:21.981
but Mary
is the expert leatherworker.

35:22.016 --> 35:25.157
Mary: I have to cut out
some thick cowhide,

35:25.192 --> 35:28.367
then the edges get cut down
so it's smooth,

35:28.402 --> 35:32.785
and everything gets glued
and stitched together.

35:32.820 --> 35:34.062
All right.

35:34.097 --> 35:35.719
Pretty good.

35:35.754 --> 35:38.032
It really feels good
to be working again.

35:38.066 --> 35:42.588
This knife is the stepping stone
to getting back into business

35:42.623 --> 35:46.385
and putting some money
down on property.

35:46.420 --> 35:50.286
Narrator:
The final step in the knife
build is to affix the handle.

35:50.320 --> 35:52.046
You need seasoned wood
for handles.

35:52.080 --> 35:54.393
This is mesquite, it's what
I use a lot in the desert.

35:54.428 --> 35:56.326
Great wood.
Real pretty.

35:56.361 --> 35:58.570
I basically start out
with two slabs,

35:58.604 --> 36:00.227
get everything
pinned into place,

36:00.261 --> 36:02.298
and then shape it down
from there.

36:04.679 --> 36:06.923
Oh.

36:06.957 --> 36:08.994
That's split all
the way through.

36:09.028 --> 36:11.445
[ Sighs ]
It cracked.

36:11.479 --> 36:12.929
Straight through.

36:12.963 --> 36:15.345
I wouldn't put anything
like this out on the market.

36:15.380 --> 36:17.830
That's the last mesquite I got.

36:17.865 --> 36:20.523
Narrator:
Mesquite grows everywhere
in the Arizona desert,

36:20.557 --> 36:22.214
but not in the Ozarks.

36:22.249 --> 36:23.974
He'll need a Plan B

36:24.009 --> 36:27.426
if he's going to make good
on this order.

36:27.461 --> 36:28.772
I've got to figure
something out,

36:28.807 --> 36:32.949
and I've got to figure
something out in a hurry.

36:32.983 --> 36:34.709
Back to the drawing board.

36:42.407 --> 36:43.994
Narrator:
In the Ozark Mountains,

36:44.029 --> 36:45.341
Jason's first project

36:45.375 --> 36:49.414
in his new makeshift forge
is nearly complete.

36:49.448 --> 36:52.865
But a last minute error
throws a wrench in his plans.

36:52.900 --> 36:54.867
The mesquite he planned
to use as a handle

36:54.902 --> 36:56.628
for the bolo knife cracked,

36:56.662 --> 37:00.218
so he's improvising
with a piece of recycled rubber.

37:00.252 --> 37:02.254
Rubber has got a couple
of advantages.

37:02.289 --> 37:04.187
It's pretty much weatherproof.

37:04.222 --> 37:05.430
It's waterproof.

37:05.464 --> 37:07.949
Makes a good shock absorber.

37:07.984 --> 37:09.261
That's gonna work.

37:09.296 --> 37:11.332
It's holed in there
pretty tight.

37:13.714 --> 37:15.681
It's grabbing hold
of that washer.

37:19.306 --> 37:21.480
Everything is held down tight.

37:21.515 --> 37:24.483
We'll start trimming off
some of this excess.

37:24.518 --> 37:27.935
Now that I've got it shaped up,
it's all looking really good.

37:27.969 --> 37:29.247
All right.

37:29.281 --> 37:30.834
Let's give her a run.

37:39.291 --> 37:40.913
Yeah.

37:40.948 --> 37:42.018
I'd say she's sharp.

37:42.052 --> 37:43.813
You give a couple
of light little whacks,

37:43.847 --> 37:46.333
and I'll tell you what,
it is six inches wide

37:46.367 --> 37:48.058
and three inches deep

37:48.093 --> 37:51.648
and there ain't a lot
of power behind it.

37:51.683 --> 37:53.063
That'll do.

37:53.098 --> 37:55.065
It will go through your finger
if you ain't careful.

37:58.103 --> 38:00.450
Well, honey, it works.
I think it cuts.

38:00.485 --> 38:02.141
That's where
that roast went.

38:02.176 --> 38:03.591
Yeah, well.

38:03.626 --> 38:06.180
[ Chuckles ] You going to clean
that out and test this?

38:06.214 --> 38:07.250
Yeah.

38:07.285 --> 38:08.769
See if it's gonna
work for you?

38:08.803 --> 38:10.805
You said you wanted
it rustic, right?

38:10.840 --> 38:13.429
I was asked for something that
looked like it had been around

38:13.463 --> 38:15.914
for a while,
and it's got a nice fit.

38:15.948 --> 38:17.605
We're going to have
to wet this down,

38:17.640 --> 38:22.300
mold it, and keep it over
by the fire so it dries out.

38:22.334 --> 38:24.302
Mary's got the sheath
almost finished.

38:24.336 --> 38:27.132
All in all, being the first
piece out of this shop,

38:27.166 --> 38:28.582
it's looking good.

38:28.616 --> 38:30.100
Given the circumstances,

38:30.135 --> 38:32.758
it just feels good
to get back to work.

38:32.793 --> 38:35.761
The most important thing
is trying to reestablish

38:35.796 --> 38:37.384
a foothold here in Arkansas

38:37.418 --> 38:39.040
and come back to your
family roots.

38:39.075 --> 38:40.801
Where it's at.

38:40.835 --> 38:43.286
And try to continue that.

38:47.152 --> 38:50.155
♪♪

38:56.126 --> 38:58.163
Narrator: In Alaska,

38:58.197 --> 39:01.408
Morgan arrives
on the outskirts of McGrath.

39:01.442 --> 39:05.343
The small town is home
to just 350 people,

39:05.377 --> 39:08.829
but for someone who spent
two years in total isolation,

39:08.863 --> 39:11.625
it's civilization.

39:11.659 --> 39:15.422
It's always really strange
being back in town.

39:15.456 --> 39:17.562
Total culture shock
because the way

39:17.596 --> 39:19.771
you go about everything
is so different.

39:19.805 --> 39:23.878
Just cars alone, you can
smell them from a mile off.

39:23.913 --> 39:26.881
Right now, it's all about
getting supplies

39:26.916 --> 39:29.367
and getting out
as quick as possible.

39:29.401 --> 39:31.507
Narrator: Morgan's mission
is to stay on budget

39:31.541 --> 39:33.267
while stocking up
on the necessities

39:33.301 --> 39:35.856
he can't grow or hunt
on his own.

39:35.890 --> 39:38.479
Last winter, he struggled
to feed his horses

39:38.514 --> 39:40.205
once the snow set in.

39:40.239 --> 39:44.071
And this year, he's determined
to get ahead of the problem.

39:44.105 --> 39:46.038
Morgan: Here's the feed.

39:46.073 --> 39:48.627
This is corn, oats, and barley

39:48.662 --> 39:52.769
blended into a mixture
that's palatable to horses.

39:52.804 --> 39:55.979
I'm going to go inside
and pay for this

39:56.014 --> 39:58.706
and have them deliver it to the
air taxi 'cause I can't --

39:58.741 --> 40:03.055
I can't carry 300 pounds
of that around.

40:03.090 --> 40:04.298
Narrator: Morgan has
just enough money

40:04.332 --> 40:06.438
to hitch a ride home
by helicopter,

40:06.473 --> 40:10.062
which can carry a maximum
cargo load of 400 pounds,

40:10.097 --> 40:12.858
so he'll have to stick
to the basics.

40:14.722 --> 40:16.068
Here we go.
Rice.

40:16.103 --> 40:18.519
We just buy stuff
that keeps a long time.

40:18.554 --> 40:20.452
Rice, beans.

40:20.487 --> 40:22.799
Kidney beans, pinto beans,
lima beans, red beans,

40:22.834 --> 40:25.008
great northern beans.

40:25.043 --> 40:27.390
Flour. Sugar.

40:27.425 --> 40:30.186
Essential for oatmeal.

40:30.220 --> 40:32.809
Looks like oranges are on sale.

40:32.844 --> 40:34.880
Those are good.
Margaret will like that,

40:34.915 --> 40:36.261
fresh fruit.

40:36.295 --> 40:37.780
That's a real big
treat out there,

40:37.814 --> 40:39.989
because it's heavy
and it goes bad.

40:40.023 --> 40:41.922
So we hardly ever eat it.

40:43.579 --> 40:46.582
♪♪

40:49.861 --> 40:51.483
Yeah.

40:51.518 --> 40:54.313
I haven't had
ice cream in months.

40:54.348 --> 40:56.764
We don't have much
of that out in the bush.

40:56.799 --> 40:57.972
I don't care.
It's cold.

40:58.007 --> 40:59.353
So that's some good stuff.

40:59.387 --> 41:01.355
Everything here is
such a luxury.

41:01.389 --> 41:04.876
You don't take it for granted,
that's for sure.

41:04.910 --> 41:05.946
There we go.

41:05.980 --> 41:08.362
Chocolate fudge chunk.

41:08.396 --> 41:11.020
That's the one.

41:11.054 --> 41:15.369
I nervously kind of watch
the register ring up.

41:15.403 --> 41:19.511
But, uh, I think I kept it
under budget so far.

41:19.546 --> 41:23.032
I'm trying to cap this trip
to town at about 500 bucks.

41:23.066 --> 41:24.620
I can't tell you what
a good feeling it

41:24.654 --> 41:27.761
is to get supplies
stocked up for the winter.

41:27.795 --> 41:30.488
But right now, I'm going
to focus on meeting up

41:30.522 --> 41:33.491
with the pilot
to hitch my ride back home.

41:33.525 --> 41:36.045
Until then I'm going
to treat myself

41:36.079 --> 41:39.048
to a pint
of chocolate ice cream.

41:39.082 --> 41:42.051
♪♪

41:42.085 --> 41:43.880
I'm looking forward
to getting home.

41:43.915 --> 41:46.780
Should be a pretty
successful trip, I hope.

41:48.747 --> 41:51.716
♪♪

41:51.750 --> 41:54.546
Narrator:
Next time on "Mountain Men"...

41:54.581 --> 41:56.583
As winter tightens its grip...

41:56.617 --> 41:58.274
Tom: I want to do
some beaver trapping,

41:58.308 --> 42:00.138
and everything is froze up.

42:00.172 --> 42:02.278
Narrator:
Tom looks to break new ground.

42:02.312 --> 42:04.142
You seeing any of that sign
in there, Tom?

42:04.176 --> 42:07.870
I don't see anything
right along here.

42:07.904 --> 42:09.665
Narrator: Marty's high hopes...

42:09.699 --> 42:11.874
Marty:
Fresh lynx track right there.

42:11.908 --> 42:14.048
I'll try and get
in a bunch of sets.

42:14.083 --> 42:16.085
Narrator: ...come crashing down.

42:16.119 --> 42:19.053
Marty: Damn it.
This isn't working.

42:19.088 --> 42:21.366
Narrator: And in the aftermath
of disaster,

42:21.400 --> 42:23.817
Eustace discovers
that the storm...

42:23.851 --> 42:26.647
Eustace: The destruction
is just overwhelming.

42:26.682 --> 42:28.476
Narrator:
...isn't done with him yet.

42:28.511 --> 42:30.962
Eustace: Full of worms.
I never thought it was

42:30.996 --> 42:33.309
going to be as quite as hard
going as it is.

42:33.343 --> 42:37.727
But we're in trouble.
